## Design an inclusive service

To design an inclusive service start with understanding your users and their needs. This is covered in [Service Standard Point 1 - Understand users and their needs](/standards/service-standard/1).

Consider whether the service is suitable for everyone. The ways in which people access a service can be limited on a permanent, temporary or situational basis. For example, a user could have hearing loss, colour blindness or have a slow internet connection. 

Sometimes, users will need help to use your service online. This is known as <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/helping-people-to-use-your-service/assisted-digital-support-introduction"  target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">assisted digital support (opens in new tab)</a>.  

## How to meet this standard

To meet government accessibility requirements, digital services must:

- meet level AA of the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/helping-people-to-use-your-service/understanding-wcag-20"  target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG 2.1) (opens in new tab)</a> as a minimum
- work on the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/technology/testing-with-assistive-technologies"  target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">most commonly used assistive technologies (opens in new tab)</a> - including screen magnifiers, screen readers and speech recognition tools
- include people with access needs in [user research](/user-research/)
- have an <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/make-your-website-or-app-accessible-and-publish-an-accessibility-statement#decide-if-anything-is-a-disproportionate-burden-to-fix-right-now"  target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">accessibility statement (opens in new tab)</a> that explains how accessible the service is - you need to publish this when the service moves into public beta

